[normal]&#xa0;[bold]&#xa0;[bold]Main Findings[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]What is the extent of white working class pupils’ educational underachievement?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]What factors do you think are responsible for white working class pupils’ educational underachievement?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Is the problem of educational underachievement particularly worse for boys or girls?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]What steps can schools take to improve the educational outcomes and attainment of white working class pupils?[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]To this question, respondents recommended:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]What role can government play in delivering improved educational outcomes for white working class pupils?[bold] [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]1)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]More work to encourage white working class parents to have and support higher aspirations for their children – this included activities such as encouraging parents to read with their children and incentivising / requiring parents to attend parents’ evenings. 
[normal]2)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]More targeted support for children from white working class backgrounds – with incentives for schools to provide this activity
[normal]3)
[normal]&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
[normal]Encouraging a greater use of social and community capital amongst children from white working class pupils. Recommendations included stimulating the economy of areas that are typically home to children from white working class backgrounds in order to ensure that there are opportunities outside of school for young people. Support for youth services was highlighted, enabling 
[normal]horizon-broadening opportunities and support for pupils outside of school/in holidays etc. Similarly, 
[normal]the suggestion was made that the national curriculum should aim to utilise more of the social and community capital that white working class pupils have in order to give students’ education a sense of context, and a sense that school can benefit them despite the fact that their parents may not have been successful at school.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]For example, within London 
[normal]almost half of London’s poorest white pupils get five good GCSEs with English and maths compared with the national average of 31% for white children on Free School Meals
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The performance of white working class children in inner-London reflects a broader advancement in the quality of schools and teaching within the capital. Over the last decade the capital’s schools have progressed from some of the country’s worst, to now being the second highest performing region – only behind outer-London. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Conclusion[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]We have responded in this way as we recognise the diversity of educational inequality and the different experiences and views of our teachers. 
[normal]&#xa0;
